<br>
As for the cost, I know some of these are rather pricy for the youngsters, and I know that some of the über folks aren't really gonna care about beefing up their primary stats (or they can make their own, for that matter). My market is those who have cash to spare on &quot;gimmick&quot; items, or those who could use a nice boost to their INT or their WIS or their CHA (or whatever), but can't afford to go buy that ultra-mega sword of überwhooptysmack for 700KPP.<br>
<br>
The fact of the matter is that most stat foods and beverages are a PITA to make, requiring both high skill and a goodly amount of materials gathering from sundry parts of the world. There are many who would rather not invest the time or the plat for either of those activities (skilling, gathering), and would rather just pay someone who enjoys doing that sort of stuff to go and do it for them, presenting them with a neat, reasonably-priced package. My original gripe was just that nobody wanted my neat, reasonably-priced package, so I was wondering if the problem was that I was overpriced (very little profit at the current price), or if someone was under-cutting my prices (it's still happening, but it's not as bad as the food market; there are some selling stat foods at a loss). I find that the answer was there was a general lack of knowledge that stat beverages are finally working and there are some really nice stat beverages available. I also find now that certain competitors (whom I will still refuse to name, but I know for a fact are reading this) are intentionally under-cutting my prices (and the prices of others). While it <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>is</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> a fair marketing ploy, it's a little hypocritical considering the source.<br>
<br>
Chase<br>
